18-AB88-3AE5256876DD</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Nicola</gtr:firstName><gtr:otherNames>Jane</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Weston</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE004369%2F1"><gtr:id>6F23F188-3A8C-46F0-A302-C2D46D491C99</gtr:id><gtr:title>The effects of global and local processing on face recognition performance</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E004369/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>The ability to accurately recognise faces is paramount to our everyday lives. Research has shown that a holistic strategy is optimal for accurate face recognition (eg, Tanaka &amp;amp; Farah, 1993; Young, Hellawell &amp;amp; Hay, 1987). Furthermore, Macrae and Lewis (2002) showed that holistic processing could be influenced by engaging in a global Navon letter task prior to face recognition. They found global Navon processing increased face recognition accuracy and local Navon processing decreased it. Subsequent research has reliably replicated this effect using a variety of methods and stimuli (eg, Perfect, 2003; Weston &amp;amp; Perfect, 2005).&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This research will develop our understanding of these results by investigating the neurological basis of the effect using FMRI techniques. One explanation for the effect is that the processing induced by the Navon task maps onto the holistic and featural aspects of a face. Therefore, this research will investigate the areas of the brain activated during the Navon task and look at whether the global and local versions of the Navon letter task increase activation in the fusiform gyrus associated with holistic and featural face processing. This will aid understanding of the modules involved in face processing and either confirm current theories and/or provide new explanations for the Navon effect.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2007-10-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-11-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>71516</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E004369/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Psychology</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>5858EC49-4786-4440-8352-1AB0B6DC5F23</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:perce